SIMPLE: torrid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Torrid
<hw>Tor"rid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>torridus</ets>, fr. <ets>torrere</ets> to parch, to burn, akin to
E. <ets>Thist</ets>: cf. F. <ets>torride</ets>. See
<er>Thirst</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Parched; dried with heat;
<as>as, a <ex>torrid</ex> plain or desert</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Barca or
Cyrene's <xex>torrid</xex> soil.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Violenty hot; drying or scorching with heat;
burning; parching.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Torrid</xex> heat.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Torrid zone</b></col> <fld>(Geog.)</fld>, <cd>that space
or board belt of the earth, included between the tropics, over which the
sun is vertical at some period of every year, and the heat is always
great.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Torridity</ent>⟦br⟧
